FAQs about hotels in Charleston

On average, 3-star hotels in Charleston cost $162 per night, and 4-star hotels in Charleston are $337 per night. If you're looking for something really special, a 5-star hotel in Charleston can be found for $513 per night, on average (based on Booking.com prices).
The average price per night for a 3-star hotel in Charleston this weekend is $277 or, for a 4-star hotel, $662. Looking for something even fancier? 5-star hotels in Charleston for this weekend cost around $908 per night, on average (based on Booking.com prices).
On average, it costs $221 per night to book a 3-star hotel in Charleston for tonight. You'll pay around $464 if you choose to stay in a 4-star hotel tonight, while a 5-star hotel in Charleston will cost around $608, on average (based on Booking.com prices).

  • Review score
    10.0

    Mount Pleasant was a great place to stay.

    Mount Pleasant was a great place to stay. Not quite as expensive as Charleston, but very easy to go to and from. Lots of great eating places in Mount Pleasant too. Shem Creek area is a favorite of ours. Lots of great restaurants all along the river with great views. Pages Okra Grill, Red's, Shelter and Saltwater were some of our favorites. Highly recommend Northcutt Plaza and Interior Motives for shopping. Interior Motives has great home accessories at great prices. Navigation was not hard, but traffic is bad. Hard to pick a weekend that doesn't have many events to draw in tourists.
    Guest review by
    Craig

    Charleston has gotten very commercialized since I was last there. I didn’t recognize places previously visited. We took a carriage tour but it appeared that a low rent housing development was included & we spent several moments there. Quite frankly I can see this anywhere & would have preferred to see more historic homes.

    What a lovely city with so much to see and endless history.

    What a lovely city with so much to see and endless history. Sullivan Island was such a lovely beach and I was surprised how warm the water was compared to the Pacific Ocean. Favorite restaurant: Poogan’s Porch - hands-down the best fried chicken, collards, and hoppin john I’ve ever eaten. Although we didn’t have a single bad meal in Charleston. Best coffee shop: Bitty & Beau’s. Everyone who works there have intellectual and developmental disabilities, and they aim to change the way this is viewed…plus, they have great coffee :) Real Hauntings Tour of Charleston was packed with history and Brandon was a great storyteller! Lots of night time tours, so fun.

    Followed by a trip
